## Practical Applications and Case Examples

### Secure Units and Adolescents

Social workers in secure units for adolescent boys (ages 12-16) encounter clients with histories of disattachment and often absent or dysfunctional family attachments. Applying attachment theory helps:

- **Develop Narrative Competence:** Facilitating coherent life stories to process trauma and build identity ([Holmes, 1993](https://www.ukessays.com/essays/social-work/attachment-theories-social-practice-5918.php?vref=1)).

- **Model Secure Attachments:** Social workers can provide consistent, reliable relationships serving as a secure base ([Cassidy & Shaver, 1999](https://www.ukessays.com/essays/social-work/attachment-theories-social-practice-5918.php?vref=1)).

- **Promote Family Attachments:** Where possible, supporting family connections to break cycles of criminal behavior ([UKEssays, 2018](https://www.ukessays.com/essays/social-work/attachment-theories-social-practice-5918.php?vref=1)).

### Therapeutic Counselling

Attachment theory informs therapeutic counselling by:

- **Recognizing Client Histories:** Understanding clients’ attachment histories to tailor interventions ([UKEssays, 2018](https://www.ukessays.com/essays/social-work/implications-for-therapeutic-counselling-social-work-essay.php?vref=1)).

- **Providing a Secure Base:** The therapist-client relationship acts as a corrective emotional experience, fostering trust and self-acceptance.

- **Addressing Dependency and Insecurity:** Exploring attachment-related dependency to promote autonomy and emotional resilience.

